=== By place ===

==== Byzantine Empire ====
* [[February 7]] &amp;ndash; [[Bardas Phokas the Younger|Bardas Phokas]] ('''the Younger''') and [[Bardas Skleros]], two members of the military elite, begin a [[Rebellion of Bardas Phokas the Younger|wide-scale rebellion]] against Emperor [[Basil II]]. They overrun [[Anatolia]], and Phokas declares himself Emperor. Basil applies for military assistance from Prince [[Vladimir the Great]], ruler of [[Kievan Rus']], who agrees to help him and sends a [[Varangians|Varangian]] army (6,000 men).&lt;ref&gt;Raffaele D'Amato (2010). Osprey: MAA - 459: ''The Varangian Guard 988–1453'', p. 6. {{ISBN|978-1-84908-179-5}}.&lt;/ref&gt;

==== Europe ====
* [[May 21]] &amp;ndash; King [[Louis V of France|Louis V]] dies during a [[hunting]] accident in the [[Forest of Halatte]] near the town of [[Senlis]]. His death at age 20 ends the [[Carolingian dynasty|Carolingian Dynasty]] founded by [[Charlemagne]] ('''the Great''') (see [[800]]). The late King's uncle, [[Charles, Duke of Lower Lorraine|Charles]] (Duke of [[Lower Lorraine]]), lays claim to the throne. Being a [[vassal]] of King [[Otto III]], the Frankish [[Nobility|nobles]] balk at the prospect of his ascension. 
* [[July 3]] &amp;ndash; [[Hugh Capet]], Count of [[Paris]], is elected and crowned King of [[France in the Middle Ages|France]] at [[Noyon]] ([[Picardy]]), by [[Adalbero (archbishop of Reims)|Adalbero]] (Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Reims|Reims]]). He becomes the first monarch of the [[House of Capet|Capetian Dynasty]], who rules the kingdom until [[1328]]. Empress-regent [[Theophanu]] (the mother of Otto III) leads an expedition to Lower Lorraine, to ensure it remains as part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]].
* [[Almanzor|Al-Mansur]], the ''[[de facto]]'' ruler of [[Al-Andalus]], occupies the city of [[Coimbra]] (modern [[Portugal]]).&lt;ref name=picard2000&gt;{{cite book|last=Picard|first=Christophe|title=Le Portugal musulman (VIIIe-XIIIe siècle). L'Occident d'al-Andalus sous domination islamique|year=2000|publisher=Maisonneuve &amp; Larose|location=Paris|isbn=2-7068-1398-9|page=109}}&lt;/ref&gt; The domination of the Andalusian authorities in the north of [[Portugal|Gharb al-Andalus]], leads to the submission of the [[County of Portugal|Counts of Portugal]] to the [[Caliphate of Córdoba]]. But it also illustrates the limited ability of the Muslims to repopulate, or at least govern directly, these remote areas.
* December &amp;ndash; The 15-year-old [[Robert II of France|Robert]] (the son of Hugo Capet) is crowned co-ruler of France around [[Christmas]] at [[Orléans]].&lt;ref&gt;Robert Fawtier, ''The Capetian Kings of France'', transl. Lionel Butler and R.J. Adam, (Macmillan, 1989), p.48.&lt;/ref&gt;
* The population of [[Bari]] revolts against the [[Byzantine Empire]].&lt;ref name=&quot;occasion of the normans&quot;&gt;{{cite journal|last=France|first=John|title=The occasion of the coming of the Normans to southern Italy|journal=Journal of Medieval History|year=1991|volume=17|issue=1|pages=183–203|doi=10.1016/0304-4181(91)90033-H}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==== Africa ====
* The [[Zirid dynasty|Zirid Dynasty]] fails to reconquer the western part of the [[Maghreb]] ('''Land of Atlas'''), which they have recently lost to the [[Umayyad Caliphate]].&lt;ref&gt;Gilbert Meynier (2010). ''L'Algérie cœur du Maghreb classique. De l'ouverture islamo-arabe au repli (658-1518)''. Paris: La Découverte; p. 45.&lt;/ref&gt;

=== By topic ===

==== Art ====
* An extension of the Prayer Hall, [[Great Mosque of Córdoba]] at [[Córdoba, Spain|Córdoba]] (modern [[Spain]]), is made.
&lt;/onlyinclude&gt;
== Births ==
* [[Al-Mahdi al-Husayn]], Zaidi [[imam]] of [[Yemen]] (d. [[1013]])
* [[Ibn Hayyan]], Moorish writer and [[historian]] (d. [[1075]])
* [[Consort Li (Zhenzong)|Li]], imperial consort of the [[Song dynasty|Song Dynasty]] (d. [[1032]])
* [[Liu Yong (Song dynasty)|Liu Yong]], Chinese [[poetry|poet]] of the Song Dynasty (d. [[1053]])

== Deaths ==
* [[January 10]] &amp;ndash; [[Pietro I Orseolo]], doge of [[Republic of Venice|Venice]] (b. [[928]])
* [[March 30]] &amp;ndash; [[Arnulf II, Count of Flanders|Arnulf II]] ('''the Younger'''), Frankish [[Nobility|nobleman]]
* [[May 21]] &amp;ndash; [[Louis V of France|Louis V]], king of the [[West Francia|West Frankish Kingdom]] 
* [[July 21]] &amp;ndash; [[Geoffrey I, Count of Anjou|Geoffrey I]] ('''Greymantle'''), Frankish nobleman
* [[November 16]] &amp;ndash; [[Shen Lun]], Chinese [[scholar-official]]
* [[Abu'l-Fawaris Ahmad ibn Ali]], Ikhshidid governor
* [[Adalbert I, Count of Vermandois|Adalbert I]], Frankish nobleman (approximate date)
* [[Beatrice of France]],  duchess [[regent]] of Upper [[Lorraine]]
* [[Erluin I of Gembloux|Erluin I]], Frankish [[Order of Saint Benedict|Benedictine]] monk and [[abbot]]
* [[Otto I, Count of Chiny|Otto I]] (or '''Eudes'''), Frankish nobleman (approximate date)
* [[Owain ap Hywel Dda]], king of [[Deheubarth]] ([[Wales]])
* [[Severus Ibn al-Muqaffa|Severus ibn al-Muqaffa]], Coptic Orthodox bishop
* [[Střezislava]], Bohemian noblewoman (approximate date)
* [[Ziyar ibn Shahrakuya]], Buyid general (approximate date)

